Faith in Free Trade
From Cambridge — — Recently I was invited to guest lecture in a globalization course taught by two Harvard colleagues. "I must warn you,"
said one of them beforehand: "These students are all strong supporters of globalization."
He had asked the students in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and over 90 percent voted for the former.
And this was before we had even begun to teach the magical effects of comparative advantage.
We know that in real surveys, asking the same question to a representative sample — — rather than Harvard students — — would yield a completely different result.
In the United States, the ratio of trade restriction opponents to supporters is 2:1.
But the answers from Harvard students would not seem particularly surprising.
Because those with higher technology and better education are often more inclined to support free trade than blue-collar workers.
Perhaps these Harvard students had already anticipated their own (financial) futures and made their decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps they simply didn't understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I deliberately changed the form of asking the same question and emphasized the potential distribution effects of trade.
The consensus supporting fair trade completely vanished, even more quickly than I had anticipated.
At the beginning, I asked everyone if they agreed with me conducting a particularly magical experiment.
I selected Nicholas and John as volunteers and told them that I had a way to make the $200 in Nicholas's account disappear —— change! —— while adding $300 to John's account, and the great achievement of social engineering could add an additional $100 value to the class as a whole.
So will they allow me to play this little trick?
The result was that only a small portion firmly agreed, many hesitated, and even more opposed the implementation of this change.

It's clearly evident that students can't stand this form of large-scale income redistribution, even if the overall economic cake has been expanded.
I then asked why most of them almost instinctively supported free trade, when free trade actually leads to a similar — in fact, even more significant — redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
Students all looked stunned.
I then said, let's assume that Nicholas and John both started competing small businesses.
John worked harder, saved and invested more, and produced better products, so he not only earned $300 more than Nicholas but also drove Nicholas's company out of the market, causing him a loss of $200.
So how many students supported this change?
This time, most of them voted in favor — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then proposed another assumption directly related to international trade.
Could John have pushed Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or by outsourcing business processes to China where labor rights are not yet fully established?
Or by employing child labor in Indonesia?
The degree of agreement with the change then decreases in order with the above options.
Additionally, technological innovation, like trade, can also place some people in a more disadvantaged position; what is your stance on this?
Only a few students are willing to restrain technological development.
To almost everyone, it is simply a foolish idea to ban the production of light bulbs in order to preserve the jobs of candle makers.
Therefore, what students oppose is not necessarily redistribution, but only certain forms of redistribution.
Like most of us, they care about the fairness of the process.
If we are to judge the results of redistribution, we must know the objective circumstances that led to such outcomes.
We do not feel resentful about the immense wealth of Bill Gates or Warren Buffett, even if some of their rivals have had difficult times, probably because they and their competitors all operate under the same basic rules and face extremely similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had become wealthy not through their own intelligence and effort, but through fraud, violating labor laws, destroying the environment, or exploiting subsidies from foreign governments, our views would be entirely different.
If we cannot tolerate redistribution that results from violating the moral standards generally accepted domestically, then on what grounds can we feel at ease about redistribution involving international transactions?
Similarly, when we expect redistribution effects to eventually lead to equality and benefit everyone in the long run, we are likely not to care much about the transfer of income.
That is also why we believe that even though technology may bring short-term negative effects to some people, it is still the key reason we are willing to promote its development.
On the other hand, when trade continuously impacts the same group of people — — low-educated blue-collar workers — — we become worried about globalization.
But many economists ignore these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute the concerns about globalization to stupid and selfish trade protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the most important issue is actually a moral one.
Since they are unable to recognize that international trade sometimes — — of course not always — — leads to redistribution consequences that we would not accept domestically, these economists are also unable to properly engage in public discussions.
How can they justify trade vigorously when their arguments are morally indefensible?
When globalization occasionally raises a thorny issue related to the legitimization of redistribution effects, we should not respond hastily by restricting trade.
There are many pros and cons that need careful consideration, including the possibility that globalization may cause wealth deprivation more severe than that suffered by people in the United States itself.
Democracies should have a more appropriate discussion on this and make conscious and more thoughtful decisions.
Yet the practice of being enamored solely because globalization enlarges the cake will eventually erode the legitimacy of globalization itself in the long run.
